What is ggplot ?

  1. Name the aesthetics, geoms, scales, and facets of the above visualisation. Also name any statistical transformations or special coordinatesystems.

aesthetic : x indicates the number of hits, y indicates the number of home runs

geom_point : each point in the plot is a baseball player with the specific hits and home runs number

geom_density_2d: indicates the density of players points distribution.

scales: x-axis is continuous, y axis is continuous.

facet: it is a 2 dimension plot

programme <- sample(c("Science", "Social Sciemce"), 32, replace = T)
gg_students <- data.frame(student_grade, student_number, programme)

  ggplot(aes(x = HmRun, y = Hits)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_density2d() +
  labs(x = "Number of Home Run", y = "Number of hits") +
  theme_minimal()

  1. Recreate the same plot once more, but now also map the variable League to the colour aesthetic and the variable Salary to the size aesthetic.
Hitters %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = HmRun, y = Hits, color = League, size = Salary)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_density2d() +
  labs(x = "Number of Home Run", y = "Number of hits") +
  theme_minimal()

  1. Look at the many different geoms on the reference website (https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/#section-layer-geoms) .

  2. Use geom_histogram() to create a histogram of the grades of the students in the gg_students dataset. Play around with the binwidth argument of the geom_histogram() function.

ggplot(data = gg_students, aes(x = student_grade)) +
  # set the width of each bin along the X-axis
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.2) +
  labs(x = "grade", y = "number of students") +
  theme_classic()

  1. Use geom_density() to create a density plot of the grades of the students in the gg_students dataset. Add the argument fill = light seagreen to geom_density() .
ggplot(data = gg_students, aes(x = student_grade)) +
  geom_density(fill = "light seagreen") +
  labs(x = "grade") +
  theme_classic()

  1. Add rug marks to the density plot through geom_rug() . You can edit the colour and size of the rug marks using those arguments within the geom_rug() function.
ggplot(data = gg_students, aes(x = student_grade)) +
  geom_density(fill = "seagreen") +
  geom_rug(color = "red", size = 0.8)

  1. Increase the data to ink ratio by removing the y axis label, setting the theme to theme_minimal() , and removing the border of the density polygon.Also set the limits of the x-axis to go from 0 to 10 using the xlim() function, because those are the plausible values for a student grade.
ggplot(data = gg_students, aes(x = student_grade)) +
  geom_density(fill = "seagreen") +
  geom_rug(color = "red", size = 0.5) +
  labs(x = "grade", y = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  xlim(2.5, 10)

  1. Create a boxplot of student grades per programme in the gg_students dataset you made earlier: map the programme variable to the x positionand the grade to the y position. For extra visual aid, you can additionally map the programme variable to the fill aesthetic.
ggplot(data = gg_students, aes(x = programme, y = student_grade, fill = programme)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "program", y = "grade")

  1. What do each of the horizontal lines in the boxplot mean? What do the vertical lines (whiskers) mean?

The horizontal line indicates the median grade in each program, the vertical line implies the quartile of each program.

  1. Comparison of distributions across categories can also be done by adding a fill aesthetic to the density plot you made earlier. Try this out. To takecare of the overlap, you might want to add some transparency in the geom_density() function using the alpha argument.
ggplot(data = gg_students, aes(x = student_grade, fill = programme)) +
  geom_density(alpha = .5) +
  labs(x = "grade")

  1. Use geom_line() to make a line plot out of the first 200 observations of the variable Volume (the number of trades made on each day) of the Smarket dataset. You will need to create a Day variable using mutate() to map to the x-position. This variable can simply be the integers from 1to 200. Remember, you can select the first 200 rows using Smarket[1:200, ] .
Smarket[1:200,] %>%
  mutate(Day = 1:200) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Day, y = Volume)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal()

  1. Give the line a nice colour and increase its size . Also add points of the same colour on top.
Smarket[1:200,] %>%
  mutate(Day = 1:200) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Day, y = Volume, fill = "blue")) +
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  geom_point(color = "blue")

  1. Use the function which.max() to find out which of the first 200 days has the highest trade volume and use the function max() to find out howlarge this volume was.
which.max(Smarket[1:200,]$Volume) #170
## [1] 170
max(Smarket[1:200,]$Volume) #2.33083
## [1] 2.33083
  1. Use geom_label(aes(x = your_x, y = your_y, label = Peak volume)) to add a label to this day. You can use either the values or call the functions. Place the label near the peak!
Smarket[1:200,] %>%
  mutate(Day = 1:200) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Day, y = Volume)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  geom_label(x = 170, y = 2.33083, label = "Peak Volume")

  1. Create a data frame called baseball based on the Hitters dataset. In this data frame, create a factor variable which splits players salary range into 3 categories. Tip: use the filter() function to remove the missing values, and then use the cut() function and assign nice labels to the categories. In addition, create a variable which indicates the proportion of career hits that was a home run.
baseball <- Hitters %>%
  drop_na(Salary) %>%
  mutate(salary_range = cut(Salary, breaks = 3, labels = c("Low", "Medium", "High")),
         hr_pro = CHmRun / CHits)
  1. Create a scatter plot where you map CWalks to the x position and the proportion you calculated in the previous exercise to the y position. Fix the yaxis limits to (0, 0.4) and the x axis to (0, 1600) using ylim() and xlim() . Add nice x and y axis titles using the labs() function. Save the plot asthe variable baseball_plot .
ggplot(data = baseball, aes(x = CWalks, y = hr_pro)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Total Number of Walk", y = "Homerun Probability") + 
  xlim(0, 1600) +
  ylim(0, 0.4)

  1. Split up this plot into three parts based on the salary range variable you calculated. Use the facet_wrap() function for this; look at the examples in the help file for tips.
ggplot(data = baseball, aes(x = CWalks, y = hr_pro)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Total Number of Walk", y = "Homerun Probability") + 
  xlim(0, 1600) +
  ylim(0, 0.4) +
  facet_wrap("salary_range")
